// itm files
@1000 = ~Poisoned Arrow~
@1001 = ~This arrow is coated with a dangerous poison that cannot be removed by ordinary means. You are to bring the arrow to Alatoasz Berendim in Duskwood Dell, Eldath’s sacred sanctuary, so that the poison may be studied and its origin traced.~
@1002 = ~Groveglove~
@1003 = ~The Groveglove is an exceptionally rare flowering plant whose waxy, foxglove-like bells bloom in shimmering hues ranging from deep violet to pale pink. It grows only in ancient, magic-laden elven groves, often near still spring pools or within the boundaries of a Mythal.

A single drop of sap is enough to kill an adult—or, in skilled hands, to craft a cure for equally lethal afflictions. Druids regard the plant with ambivalence: as a natural part of the world’s balance, but also as a reminder that even the most beautiful gifts of nature can be deadly.

You must deliver one of these blossoms to Alatoasz Berendim in Duskwood Dell.

Notable Traits:
Found only in elven groves under the influence of strong nature magic.~
@1004 = ~Fungal Key~
@1005 = ~This key is overgrown with grime and strange spores. It appears to open a very particular kind of door.~
@1006 = ~Supplier's Note~
@1007 = ~Skann, I need you to deliver a large shipment of my work to several interested parties. Meet me at the marked location at Toadstool Hollow. Destroy this note so it doesn’t fall into the wrong hands.

Delgorth~
@1008 = ~Keltormir, the Fallen Empire~
@1009 = ~Keltormir, the Fallen Empire
by Elenneth Moonsyl, Sage of Evereska

“All forests remember. Even when the trees fall and the songs fade, the roots hold the memory.”

In the elder days of Toril, long before the rise of Calimshan or Tethyr, the ancient forest empire of Keltormir stretched across the south of Faerûn like a green ocean. Bound by reverence to the Seldarine and governed by harmony with nature, the elves of Keltormir built their realms not in defiance of the land, but in communion with it.

Among the most enduring legacies of Keltormir were its three mythal-guarded cities, each a beacon of elven magic and culture—each now lost, faded, or fallen: Myth Rhynn, Myth Unnohyr and Myth Tellaren.

Myth Rhynn
Hidden deep within the Mytharan Woods, in the shadowed reaches of the Wealdath, lies Myth Rhynn, once a hallowed necropolis of the elves. Its mythal, unlike those of other elven cities, was not wrought for war or wonder, but for reverence. But the mythal is broken. Whether shattered by age, sacrilege, or forgotten sorrow, it no longer binds the dead to sleep. Now, shadows walk among the roots of ancient barrows, and unquiet spirits rise in the stillness. Even the elves who once came to honor their ancestors now avoid the place, for the broken threads of the mythal pull at their hearts, as if mourning its own fall. What was once a sacred resting place is now a sorrowful wound upon the forest—and a warning.

Myth Unnohyr
The darkest tale among the three, Myth Unnohyr rose in the shadowed valleys of Tethyr’s southern forests. Its magic once fostered growth, healing, and deep communion with the natural world. Yet long before the Time of Troubles, something began to unravel. Elven lore speaks in hushed tones of a faltering divine bond—of a protector whose waning strength left the city's heart exposed. When that sacred power faded, the mythal shattered in silent despair, birthing a zone of wild and dead magic—a festering wound upon the Weave that endures to this day. Now, few dare to approach its ruins, where even divine power falters, and the poisoned soil hums with restless malice.

Myth Tellaren
Far to the south, in lands now buried under the sands of the desert, stood Myth Tellaren. When the genie-lords of Calim and Memnon warred across the south, their chaos reached even the hidden places of the elves. Myth Tellaren’s mythal, strained by planar pressure and betrayal from within, fractured—and with it, the delicate magic that held the city aloft. The destruction was swift and near-total. Some say the ruin still exists beneath the shifting sands, frozen in a moment of magical collapse—its mythal broken, yet still pulsing faintly, like embers beneath ash.

Though Keltormir has faded into myth, the echoes of its greatness endure. Where trees grow thick and stars fall strangely, where magic sings through stone or refuses to stir—there, the empire of leaves once stood. And perhaps, may rise again.~
@1010 = ~Fragment of an Amulet~
@1011 = ~This is a fragment of a pendant, depicting three intertwined golden rings—a sacred symbol once revered by an ancient elven guardian of magic and unity. Though incomplete, the fragment still resonates faintly with the corrupted mythal of Myth Unnohyr. When held, you feel the oppressive forces around you soften slightly, as if the fractured Weave remembers its original purpose. Yet without the full amulet, its protective strength remains useless.~
@1012 = ~Head of an Elf~
@1013 = ~This is the severed head of what was once a strikingly handsome elven man. Around his neck, strands of long, silken hair remain tightly coiled—still clinging to him in death. It appears he was strangled… not by rope or cord, but by someone’s hair.~  
@1014 = ~Golden Chain~
@1015 = ~This is a finely wrought golden chain, crafted with meticulous care to once bear a splendid amulet. Though the medallion itself has been lost to time, the chain retains a faint, lingering trace of its ancient enchantment—a whisper of a forgotten duty to shield and preserve.~
@1016 = ~Talisman of the First Binding~
@1017 = ~Forged during the founding of Myth Unnohyr, this talisman bore the symbol of three intertwined rings, embodying harmony between divine power and arcane craft. It was created to anchor the city's mythal, a testament to the unity between faith and magic. 

Even as centuries of ruin dulled its brilliance, the talisman preserves a fragile echo of its former strength. In the presence of this relic, the wild surges and dead magic of the broken mythal falter, offering precious protection to those who dare walk the fallen city's shattered streets.

Equipped abilities: 
– Immunity to wild magic and dead magic zone effects in Myth Unnohyr

Weight: 0~
@1018 = ~Necklace of Life~
@1019 = ~Simple in appearance, yet suffused with quiet power, this necklace pulses faintly with restorative energy. Though its origins remain unclear, it is often favored by healers, peacewardens, and those who walk where death's shadow lingers.

The amulet seems to repel the chill of necromantic energies and lends renewed strength to those who wear it—bolstering both body and spirit in equal measure.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Saving Throw vs. Necromancy: +5  
– Maximum Hit Points: +2  

Weight: 0~
@1020 = ~Springwater of Eldath~
@1021 = ~Drawn from a spring where Eldath’s blessing flows undisturbed, this sacred draught carries more than mere healing. It is said that the water remembers the shape of peace—cleansing not only wounds and sickness, but also breaking curses that bind the soul.

Those who drink of it feel not only restored in body, but unburdened—as though a gentle current carried their troubles away.

STATISTICS:

Special: Cures poison and disease, removes curses, and heals 5 Hit Points

Weight: 1~
@1022 = ~Singing Water of Eldath~
@1023 =~This is a bottle of Singing Water of Eldath. It is one of the ingredients needed to create an antidote for a poison created by a priest of Talona.
  
STATISTICS:

Weight: 1~
@1024 = ~Will-o'-wisp's attack~
@1025 = ~Will-o'-pox's attack~
@1026 = ~Bell~
@1027 = ~Bell of Erlavanas Myth'yalv~
@1028 = ~Bells like these are music instruments. Bells most often have the shape of an empty cup. When struck, it vibrates in a single strong strike tone. Some noblemen and noblewomen also use this instrument to call their servants, but many artists wouldn't call it a proper use of such item.
  
STATISTICS:

Weight: 0~
@1029 = ~This bell is an old elven instrument, bound witht the spirit of an elven traitor, Erlavanas Myth'yalv. He was once called the "Traitor of the Mythal". What exactly were his crimes, it is hard to say. Tales of this man never survived the trial of time. Unlike as his spirit, as it looks like this bell can still call him and force him to fight on the side of anyone that has this bell.

STATISTICS:

Charge abilities:
– May call the spirit of Erlavanas Myth'yalv once per day

Weight: 0~
@1030 = ~Spectre's Ring~
@1031 = ~Helmet~
@1032 = ~Helmet of Elven Chants~
@1033 = ~This helmet is known as Helmet of Elven Chants and was created by a powerful elven blacksmith. If legends are to be belived, when worn by elves, the helmet improves their natural abilities, as well as it allows to summon an old elven chant that will aid the one that wears this headgear and their allies.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Protects against critical hits
– Dexterity: +2 (elves only), +1 (half-elves only)

Charge abilities:
– May cast Chant once per day

Weight: 0~
@1034 = ~Longsword~
@1035 = ~Blade of the Elven Mycologist +3~
@1036 = ~This sword used to belong to an elven mycologist, Vicjane Fol-Truvé. She was known to be one of the most skilled mycologists in Amn. While she knew how to fight myconids, she considered it her last resort, and she would rather try to communicate with them, study their culture. If she had no other choice, though, she would use that exact sword against them.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities: 
– Magic Resistance: +5%
– Armor Class vs. Myconids: +2
– Saving Throws vs. Myconids: +2

THAC0: +3
Damage: 1d8+3, +1 acid damage, +1 fire damage
Damage type: Slashing
Speed Factor: 3
Proficiency Type: Long Sword
Type: One-handed
Requires:
 6 Strength

Weight: 4~
@1037 = ~Ioun Stone~
@1038 = ~Berry-Shaped Ioun Stone~
@1039 = ~This Ioun stone is shaped like a berry. Someone must have used magic to make it look like this.
  
STATISTICS:

Weight: 0~
@1040 = ~This Ioun stone is believed to have been created by a powerful cleric of Talona. Shaped like a sour green berry, it carries a sharp, unripe scent that lingers unpleasantly in the air.

Whispers among the faithful claim that certain Talonites used stones like this to deal with rival priests—especially those who stood in the way of their poison-laced ambitions. Unsurprisingly, the stone refuses to attune to those of a good-aligned nature.

STATISTICS:

Combat abilities:
– THAC0 vs. Clerics: +3

Special abilities:
– When carried or equipped, this Ioun stone dispels the poisonous fumes blocking the entrance to the tower in Myth Unnohyr

Weight: 0~
@1041 = ~Studded Leather~
@1042 = ~The Blessed Wyvern +3~
@1043 = ~This studded leather armor is known under the name The Blessed Wyvern and it is believed to protect its wearer by granting them regeneration, but it's also able to manipulate the probability thus it grants its user a boost of luck.
  
Some say it was named after a wyvern called Lucretia.
  
STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities: 
– Luck: +1
– Regenerates 1 Hit Point per round

Armor Class: 4 (2 vs. slashing, 3 vs. piercing and missile)
Requires:
 6 Strength

Weight: 8~
@1044 = ~Celestial Antidote~
@1045 = ~Celestial Antidote~
@1046 = ~This is an antidote you created at Myth Unnohyr. It should be able to heal those poisoned by a powerful toxin created from flowers that grow at the ruins.
  
STATISTICS:

Weight: 1~
@1047 = ~Cloak~
@1048 = ~Eldath's Embrace~
@1049 = ~This enchanted cloak dates back to Daraniel of the Still Waters, a reclusive priest of Eldath who wandered the groves of Wealdath in ages past. Birds would nest in his hands, wolves guarded his sleep, and even the most skittish beasts would draw near to bask in his tranquil presence.
When he passed from the world, it is said dryads wove this mantle from the leaves that had fallen around his resting place. Those who wear it walk in quiet grace—and the wild things of the world walk beside them.

When animals are near, the cloak responds with gentle magic. Its wearer becomes more grounded, harder to frighten, and more difficult to strike.
  
STATISTICS:

Charge abilities:
– May cast Slow Poison once per day (on self)

Equipped abilities:
– Armor Class: +2
– Saving Throws: +2
– Move Silently: +10%
– 5% chance to cast Sanctuary when the cloak’s wearer is hit in combat.
– When animals are within 10 feet:
 - Additional +1 to AC
 - Additional +1 to Saving Throws
 - Immunity to Fear effects

Weight: 3~
@1050 = ~Redhive Flower~
@1051 = ~This beautiful, sweet-scented flower is a gift from a boy living in Duskwood Dell to his aunt in Athkatla’s Government District. He asks you to deliver the flower along with a message: That he is safe, and simply needs some time apart.

STATISTICS:
Weight: 1~
@1052 = ~Earthworm~
@1053 = ~This earthworm smells of wet ground and... pumpkins. It looks very pink and it acts quite lively. Apart from that, there is nothing unusual about it.
  
STATISTICS: 

Weight: 0~
@1054 = ~Emblem~
@1055 = ~Holy Symbol of Eldath~
@1057 = ~This is a simple emblem depicting Eldath's symbol, carved with care and reverence. Though unassuming in appearance, it seems to offer quiet protection to those who honor the goddess of peace. Its influence subtly guides the bearer away from aggression—enhancing defense while diminishing the drive to strike.
  
STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Armor Class: +1
– Saving Throws: +1
– THAC0: -2

Weight: 0~
@1058 = ~Shield Fragment~
@1059 = ~This appears to be the central piece of a shield. Without the outer frame, however, it is unusable.
  
STATISTICS:

Weight: 0~
@1060 = ~This appears to be the central piece of a shield. Without the outer frame, however, it is unusable.
  
STATISTICS:

Weight: 0~
@1061 = ~This appears to be the outer frame of a shield. Without its central component, however, it is unusable.
  
STATISTICS:

Weight: 0~
@1062 = ~Buckler~
@1063 = ~The Leafrunner +3~
@1064 = ~This elegant buckler once belonged to a druid-guardian named Blasanna Leafrunner, from whom it takes its name. When a gnoll warband threatened her grove and kin, Blasanna stood alone before them. Legends tell that she moved with the swiftness of a storm wind, striking down half the invaders before the rest fled in terror.

Some claim her speed came from the buckler itself, its magic lending her the grace of the wild. Others believe it was the forest’s own spirit that bore her onward, unwilling to see its protector fall.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Armor Class: +4
– No protection against missile and piercing attacks
– Movement rate increased by 1; increased by 2 in forests
– Saving Throws vs. Invocation School: +2

Requires:
 4 Strength

Weight: 2~
@1065 = ~Herbal Brew in a Mug~
@1066 = ~This brew is made of chamomile, wild honey, blackberry and lavender. It's supposed to calm people down. You are to bring this brew to the sirine by the water in Duskwood Dell, so that she may find peace.
  
STATISTICS: 

Weight: 2~
@1067 = ~Delgorth's Note~
@1068 = ~First Entry:
The Groveglove... the legends were true. It blooms still amidst the shattered remnants of Myth Unnohyr, where dead magic festers and life warps. Each petal hums with quiet malice, steeped in a power neither divine nor mortal. Talona smiles upon my discovery.

Second Entry:
With painstaking effort, I have distilled the first batches of the toxin. Small quantities only—precious drops of death, born of the Vein’s purple heart. Already, the results have exceeded expectations: swift, incurable, a silencer of both flesh and spirit.

Third Entry:
My first shipments have been delivered to certain enemies of the Harpers. Petty lords, disillusioned sellswords, and those who see the Harpers' meddling as a threat to true balance. Let the self-righteous choke on their piousness.

Fourth Entry:
The Night Masks in Westgate see potential. They offer coin and bodies to spread the work, but they lack subtlety. I must tread carefully. The Zhentarim, ever watchful, may prove useful—if kept at arm’s length.

Fifth Entry:
The foundations here in Myth Unnohyr are firm enough—its wild and dead magic shields my work from unwanted eyes. Though I have managed to cultivate a few vines within the dead soil, they grow slowly, stubbornly, yielding but scant blossoms. At this rate, it will take seasons to produce enough toxin for the ambitions I nurture. I must seek a way to quicken their growth—or secure more hands willing to tend the cursed harvest.

Sixth Entry:
This Eldathyn interfered, and paid for his foolishness. Others may come, but the path is clear: the toxin will spread. It will seep into the veins of Faerûn’s mighty and humble alike. Talona’s will is woven into every trembling breath they take.

Let the strong fall and the weak wither. Only decay is eternal!
May all who breathe know suffering—and in their final, gasping moments, know Her name.

— Malagent Delgorth
~
@1071 = ~Longsword~
@1072 = ~The Memory of the Myths +5~
@1073 = ~This blade once belonged to Telva, an elven knight. Tales tell of its edge striking true through the armored husks of skeletal warriors, unraveling the wards of liches, and even drawing blood from the veins of vampires. In one final, desperate struggle, the weapon was turned against a dracolich itself.
Though the dracolich summoned all its foul might and shattered the sword, the enchantments and faith bound within the steel did not perish. Instead, they flared outward—reshaping the weapon into a spectral blade of unwavering purpose.

Since that day, the sword can no longer harm the living. But against the undead, its power has only grown—capable of piercing both decaying flesh and incorporeal forms alike. Any creature tainted by undeath should fear its ghostly edge.

STATISTICS:

Combat abilities:
– Can only harm undead creatures
– Does not receive bonus damage from Strength
– Critical hits do not deal bonus damage
– 20% chance on hit to deal 2d8+5 additional fire damage to undead (Save vs. Spells at –5 to halve)
– 10% chance on hit to instantly destroy undead target

THAC0: +5
Damage: 2d8+5 (magic, vs. undead only)
Speed Factor: 3
Proficiency Type: Long Sword
Type: One-handed
Requires:
 6 Strength

Weight: 2
~

@1075 = ~Headband~
@1076 = ~Halo of Corrosive Blood~
@1077 = ~This sinister halo is fashioned from congealed, darkened blood. Once worn by an ancient creature imprisoned beneath Myth Unnohyr—an elder blood amniote—it still pulses faintly, as if remembering the rhythm of a long-forgotten heart.

Those who don the halo may channel its corrosive essence, spreading decay and agony in equal measure. To some, such pain is a curse... to others, a final and perfect gift.

STATISTICS:

Charge abilities:
– May cast Dolorous Decay once per day

Equipped abilities:
– Charisma: –1
– Acid Resistance: +10%
– 25% chance that an attacker striking the wearer suffers 1d2 acid damage (Save vs. Death at –2 negates)

Weight: 1
~
@1078 = ~Dagger~
@1079 = ~Scolopendra's Spit +3~
@1080 = ~This powerful dagger is an ideal weapon for spellcasters, especially those that specialize in summonig all sorts of acidic creations and projectiles. It does not only improve caster's abilities, but also allows such adventurers to attack enemies from a distance.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Decrease spellcasting time by 1
– Immunity to poison

Combat abilities:
– Acid Damage dealt: +10%
– Does allow to make both melee and ranged attacks

THAC0: +3
Damage (melee): 1d4+3 (piercing), +1 Acid damage
Damage (ranged): 1d4+3 (acid)
Speed Factor: 1
Proficiency Type: Dagger
Type: One-handed
Requires:
 3 Strength

Weight: 1
~
@1081 = ~Robe~
@1082 = ~Wyrd's Ended Slumber~
@1083 = ~This robe is known as wyrd's Ended Slumber and it won't be very surprising to say that it was once used by a wyrd from Myth Unnohyr. It feels like it might have looked similar to one of the robes of archimagi, but it was clearly warped by time and wyrd's influence. 

STATISTICS:

Charge abilities:
– May cast Haste once per day (self-centered)
– May cast Melf's Minute Meteors once per day 

Equipped abilities:
– Armor Class: 5
– Magic Resistance: +5%
– Caster level (arcane): +4

Weight: 6
~
@1084 = ~Staff~
@1085 = ~Branch of Duskwood Dell +3~
@1086 = ~This quarterstaff was cut long ago from a living tree within Duskwood Dell. The branch still bears a faint emerald sheen, and when held, it thrums softly with life. It was not made to kill, but to ward and to guide. Those who wield it find their strength tempered by serenity, their hearts anchored in quiet purpose.

STATISTICS:

Charge abilities:
– May cast Goodberry twice per day 

Equipped abilities:
– Immune to Entangle and Web
– Maximum Hit Points: +20%
– Saving Throws vs. Death: +2

THAC0: +3
Damage: 1d2 (non-lethal)
Speed Factor: 2
Proficiency Type: Quarterstaff
Type: Two-handed
Requires:
 5 Strength

Weight: 3
~
@1087 = ~Rose of Eldath~
@1088 = ~This is a rose blossom blessed by a priest of Eldath. When consumed, it gently restores the life energy of the afflicted, reversing any previous level drain caused by unnatural forces or undead creatures. Its petals hum with quiet mercy—offering peace not through strength, but through renewal.

STATISTICS:

Special: Removes all level drain effects from the target

Weight: 1~
@1089 = ~Two-Handed Sword~
@1090 = ~Good Luck, Honeysuckle +3~
@1091 = ~This finely balanced two-handed sword once belonged to a ranger named Vala’ll Stormneedle, a beloved protector of the Larswood region. He was known not only for his skill in battle, but for the joy with which he lived—a perfect life, a loving family, and his wife named Systianna, a faithful of Tymora.

Before each mission, she would kiss his cheek and hand him the blade, whispering, “Good luck, honeysuckle.” Unlike many folk heroes whose tales end in blood, the legend of Vala’ll is one of rare peace: He lived with Systianna until the age of eighty, passing not to sword or spell, but to pneumonia.

Some believe it was this very sword that shielded him all those years—a silent companion preserving his life long beyond the span of most who walk with steel in hand. 
  
STATISTICS:

Combat abilities:
– Each successful hit has a 15% chance to lower the target's Luck by 1 point for 2 rounds (Save vs. Spell at –4 negates), while increasing the wielder's Luck by 1 point for an entire day.

THAC0: +3
Damage: 1d10+3 (slashing)
Speed Factor: 7
Proficiency Type: Two-handed Sword
Type: Two-handed
Requires:
 14 Strength

Weight: 9~
@1092 = ~Light Crossbow~
@1093 = ~Thornshooter +1~
@1094 =~This unique crossbow conjures its own magical thorn-bolts: Sharp, barbed projectiles that can cause enemies to become entangled on impact.

Due to the nature of the druidic enchantments woven into the weapon, only single-class druids are able to wield it effectively.

STATISTICS:

Equipped Abilities:
– Sets Crossbow Proficiency to 1

Combat Abilities:
– Does not require ammunition; fires conjured magical thorn-bolts
– 20% chance per hit to entangle the target (Save vs. Spell at -1 negates)

THAC0: +1
Damage: 1d6+1 (missile)
Speed Factor: 4
Proficiency Type: Crossbow
Type: Two-handed
Requires:
 8 Strength

Weight: 6~
@1095 = ~Create Mystic Candle (Mage)~
@1096 = ~Create Mystic Candle (Level 5) has been added to your priest spellbook.~
@1097 = ~Create Mystic Candle (Level 5) has been added to your mage spellbook.~
@1098 = ~Create Mystic Candle (Priest)~
@1099 = ~Create Mystic Candle
(Evocation)

Level: 5
Range: 0
Duration: 24 hours
Casting Time: 8
Area of Effect: The caster
Saving Throw: None

This spell allows the caster to create a Mystic Candle capable of holding a special enchantment, which may be triggered when the candle is used. The caster can channel magical power and certain ingredients into the candle, storing the spell for later use. Each color of candle produces a different effect:

Red - Charm Person or Mammal
Blue - Protection from Evil, 10' radius
Purple - Know Alignment  
Gold - Cure Medium Wounds
Yellow - Command
Green - Luck
White - Neutralize Poison
Silver - Draw Upon Holy Might
Black - Doom

The candle may be used by the caster or another character, provided they have at least 12 or more Wisdom. After twenty four hours passes, the candle is destroyed.~
@1100 = ~Create Mystic Candle
(Evocation)

Level: 5
Range: 0
Duration: 24 hours
Casting Time: 8
Area of Effect: The caster
Saving Throw: None

This spell allows the caster to create a Mystic Candle capable of holding a special enchantment, which may be triggered when the candle is used. The caster can channel magical power and certain ingredients into the candle, storing the spell for later use. Each color of candle produces a different effect:

Red - Charm Person or Mammal (up to 3 targets)
Blue - Protection from Evil, 10' radius
Purple - Know Alignment (up to 3 targets)
Gold - Cure Medium Wounds
Yellow - Command (up to 3 targets)
Green - Luck (up to 3 targets)
White - Neutralize Poison
Silver - Draw Upon Holy Might
Black - Doom (up to 3 targets)

The candle may be used by the caster or another character, provided they have at least 12 or more Wisdom. After twenty four hours passes, the candle is destroyed.
~
